\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1 5. In January 2005, a company that monitors Internet traffic (WebSideStory) reported\par
that its sampling revealed that the Mozilla Firefox browser launched in 2004 had\par
grabbed a 4.6% share of the market.\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl240\slmult1 I. If the sample were based on 2,000 users, could Microsoft conclude that\par
Mozilla has a less than 5% share of the market?\par
\cf2 Ans : If the sample were based on 2,000 users and found Mozilla's share at\par
 4.6%, Microsoft cannot confidently say that Mozilla has less than a 5% share. \par
The 4.6% is an estimate based on a sample, and there's a margin of error. \par
Without more information, it's uncertain.\cf0\par
II. WebSideStory claims that its sample includes all the daily Internet users. If\par
that\rquote s the case, then can Microsoft conclude that Mozilla has a less than 5%\par
share of the market?\par
\cf2 Ans : Even if WebSideStory claims to include all daily Internet users in their\par
sample, estimating Mozilla's share at 4.6%, Microsoft still can't definitively \par
conclude that Mozilla has less than a 5% share. Sampling all Internet users is \par
challenging, and without more details, the estimate's accuracy remains \par
uncertain.\cf0\par

\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1 6. A book publisher monitors the size of shipments of its textbooks to university\par
bookstores. For a sample of texts used at various schools, the 95% confidence\par
interval for the size of the shipment was 250 \'b1 45 books. Which, if any, of the\par
following interpretations of this interval are correct?\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl240\slmult1 A. All shipments are between 205 and 295 books.\par
\cf2 Ans : \b Incorrect\b0 : This interpretation assumes that every single shipment falls \par
within the specified range. However, the 95% confidence interval does not \par
provide certainty about individual shipments but rather about the population \par
mean.\par
\cf0 B. 95% of shipments are between 205 and 295 books.\par
\cf2 Ans : \b Incorrect\b0 : This interpretation suggests that 95% of individual shipments \par
fall within the range. However, the confidence interval is about the population \par
mean, not individual shipments. It does not provide information about the \par
percentage of individual shipments within the range.\par
\cf0 C. The procedure that produced this interval generates ranges that hold the\par
population mean for 95% of samples.\par
\cf2 Ans : \b Correct\b0 : This interpretation is accurate. The 95% confidence interval   \par
(250 \'b1 45 books) indicates that if you take many samples and compute \par
confidence intervals in the same way, about 95% of those intervals will \par
contain the true population mean. It is about the reliability of the procedure \par
in capturing the population mean.\par
\cf0 D. If we get another sample, then we can be 95% sure that the mean of this\par
second sample is between 205 and 295.\par
\cf2 Ans : \b Incorrect\b0 : The confidence interval applies to the population mean, not to \par
individual sample means. Taking another sample does not guarantee that its \par
mean will fall within the specific range of 205 to 295.\par
\cf0 E. We can be 95% confident that the range 160 to 340 holds the population\par
mean.\par
\cf2 Ans : Incorrect: This statement is not supported by the given confidence \par
interval. The 95% confidence interval calculated was 250 \'b1 45 books, not 160 \par
to 340 books. This range is not derived from the confidence interval provided.\par

